{"type":"message","id":"290f5755","parentId":"8ec37082","timestamp":"2026-03-22T07:56:07.985Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_ff0e2ujybzvc_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"        success: true,\n        message: 'Mock data retrieved',\n        timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),\n        data: state[resource],\n        meta: { total: state[resource].length }\n    } : state[resource];\n}\n\n/**\n * Handles POST request to create a new item\n *\n * @param state - The server state containing stored resources\n * @param resource - The resource name to add to\n * @param req - The route request object containing the body\n * @param wrap - Whether to wrap the response in a success envelope\n * @returns The created item with generated ID and timestamps\n */\nfunction handlePost(\n    state: ServerState,\n    resource: string,\n    req: RouteRequest,\n    wrap: boolean\n): JSONValue {\n    const bodyObj = typeof req.body === 'object' && req.body !== null ? req.body as Record<string, unknown> : {};\n    const newItem: Record<string, JSONValue> = {\n        id: (bodyObj.id as string) || uuidv4(),\n        ...bodyObj as Record<string, JSONValue>,\n        createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),\n        updatedAt: new Date().toISOString()\n    };\n    state[resource].push(newItem);\n\n    return wrap ? { success: true, data: newItem, message: 'Created successfully' } : newItem;\n}\n\n/**\n * Handles PUT request to update an existing item\n *\n * @param state - The server state containing stored resources\n * @param resource - The resource name to update in\n * @param req - The route request object containing params and body\n * @param wrap - Whether to wrap the response in a success envelope\n * @returns The updated item\n */\nfunction handlePut(\n    state: ServerState,\n    resource: string,\n    req: RouteRequest,\n    wrap: boolean\n): JSONValue {\n\n[197 more lines in file. Use offset=205 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774166167983}}
{"type":"message","id":"33f2307c","parentId":"290f5755","timestamp":"2026-03-22T07:56:17.625Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full flow. Here's my integration plan:\n\n1. In `ServerGenerator`, create a `WorldState` instance\n2. When entities are created (in `handlePost`) or generated (in `handleGetById`, `handleGetCollection`), register them with WorldState and resolve FKs\n3. The WorldState lives on `ServerGenerator.world`\n\nThe cleanest approach: Store `WorldState` on `ServerState` under a special key `_world`. The handlers already receive `state: ServerState` so they can access it.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The `ServerState` is passed to handlers but the handlers are created by `createRouteHandler` which doesn't have access to the ServerGenerator instance.\n \nI could attach WorldState to ServerState directly under a special key, then modify the handler factory to resolve foreign keys when creating new entities. Or I could add a getter on ServerGenerator that gives handlers access to WorldState through closure. The cleanest path is probably extending `createRouteHandler` to accept WorldState and handle FK resolution there, then registering entities with it when they're created. But that means threading WorldState through the initialization chain. Let me trace how `generateFromSchema` actually wires everything together.","thinkingSignature":"9339a3ecdf2671dbf3ec03fb944fe3a43766580f675ac2d99b58b51a78e43e8e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_4dy1ufsq9fy0_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\dev\\schemock-app\\src\\generators\\server.ts","offset":240,"limit":150}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":51838,"output":322,"cacheRead":12454,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":64614,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774166167987}}
{"type":"message","id":"0f1e2fa1","parentId":"33f2307c","timestamp":"2026-03-22T07:56:17.632Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_4dy1ufsq9fy0_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"   * Starts the mock server on the configured port.\n   *\n   * Begins listening for HTTP requests and tracks all active connections for proper cleanup.\n   * Logs available routes in debug mode.\n   *\n   * @throws {PortError} When the configured port is already in use\n   * @throws {ServerError} When the server fails to start for other reasons\n   * @returns Promise that resolves when the server is successfully started\n   */\n  public async start(): Promise<void> {\n    // Check if server is already running\n    if (this.server && this.server.listening) {\n      const port = this.config.server.port !== undefined ? this.config.server.port : 3000;\n      throw new PortError(`Server is already running on port ${port}`, port);\n    }\n\n    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n      const port = this.config.server.port !== undefined ? this.config.server.port : 3000;\n\n      this.isStopping = false;\n\n      this.server = this.app.listen(port, () => {\n        log.info(`Mock server started`, {\n          module: 'server',\n          port,\n          url: `http://localhost:${port}`\n        });\n\n        // Log all available routes in debug mode\n        if (this.config.server.logLevel === 'debug') {\n          log.debug('Available routes:', {\n            module: 'server',\n            routes: Object.entries(this.config.routes).map(([path, config]) =>\n              `${config.method.toUpperCase()} ${path}`\n            )\n          });\n        }\n\n        resolve();\n      });\n\n      // Track all connections for proper cleanup\n      this.server.on('connection', (socket) => {\n        if (this.isStopping) {\n          // Reject new connections if we're stopping\n          socket.destroy();\n        } else {\n          this.connections.add(socket);\n\n          socket.on('close', () => {\n            this.connections.delete(socket);\n          });\n\n          socket.on('error', () => {\n            this.connections.delete(socket);\n          });\n        }\n      });\n\n      this.server.on('error', (error: NodeJS.ErrnoException) => {\n        if (error.code === 'EADDRINUSE') {\n          const portError = new PortError(`Port ${port} is already in use`, port);\n          log.error('Failed to start server', {\n            module: 'server',\n            error: portError,\n            port\n          });\n          reject(portError);\n        } else {\n          log.error('Server error', {\n            module: 'server',\n            error,\n            port\n          });\n          reject(new ServerError(error.message, { originalError: error }));\n        }\n      });\n    });\n  }\n\n  /**\n   * Stops the server gracefully, allowing existing connections to complete.\n   *\n   * Waits up to 5 seconds for connections to close before forcing them shut.\n   * If the server is not running, returns immediately.\n   *\n   * @throws {ServerError} When an error occurs while stopping the server\n   * @returns Promise that resolves when the server is stopped\n   */\n  public async stop(): Promise<void> {\n    if (!this.server) {\n      return;\n    }\n\n    this.isStopping = true;\n\n    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n      const timeout = setTimeout(() => {\n        // Force close all connections if timeout is reached\n        log.warn('Server stop timeout, forcing connections closed', {\n          module: 'server'\n        });\n        this.connections.forEach(socket => {\n          try {\n            if (typeof socket === 'object' && socket !== null && 'destroy' in socket && typeof socket.destroy === 'function') {\n              socket.destroy();\n            }\n          } catch (e) {\n            // Ignore errors when destroying sockets\n          }\n        });\n        this.connections.clear();\n\n        if (this.server) {\n          this.server.close((err) => {\n            const errno = err as NodeJS.ErrnoException;\n            if (err && errno.code !== 'ERR_SERVER_NOT_RUNNING') {\n              log.error('Error stopping server (forced)', {\n                module: 'server',\n                error: err\n              });\n            }\n            this.server = null;\n            log.info('Server stopped (forced)', { module: 'server' });\n            resolve();\n          });\n        } else {\n          this.server = null;\n          resolve();\n        }\n      }, 5000); // 5 second timeout for graceful shutdown\n\n      this.server!.close((err) => {\n        clearTimeout(timeout);\n\n        if (err) {\n          const errno = err as NodeJS.ErrnoException;\n          if (errno.code === 'ERR_SERVER_NOT_RUNNING') {\n            // Server already stopped, just clean up\n            this.connections.forEach(socket => {\n              try {\n                if (typeof socket === 'object' && socket !== null && 'destroy' in socket && typeof socket.destroy === 'function') {\n                  socket.destroy();\n                }\n              } catch (e) {\n                // Ignore errors when destroying sockets\n              }\n            });\n            this.connections.clear();\n            this.server = null;\n\n[150 more lines in file. Use offset=390 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774166177629}}
{"type":"message","id":"22cb5061","parentId":"0f1e2fa1","timestamp":"2026-03-22T07:56:22.326Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me look at how routes are set up from the schema, specifically `generateFromSchema`:","thinkingSignature":"44cc5a0d42ee1228351a6d6593f8d32014aada231c294ec8558877439082cdd6"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_9oln0wtkf4gx_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\dev\\schemock-app\\src\\generators\\server.ts","offset":450,"limit":100}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":53225,"output":85,"cacheRead":12454,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":65764,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774166177633}}
{"type":"message","id":"6d56f051","parentId":"22cb5061","timestamp":"2026-03-22T07:56:22.333Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_9oln0wtkf4gx_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"      if (this.config.server.logLevel) {\n        setLogLevel(this.config.server.logLevel);\n      }\n      this.app = express();\n      this.setupMiddleware();\n      this.setupRoutes();\n    }\n\n    await this.start();\n  }\n\n  /**\n   * Checks if the server is currently running and listening for connections.\n   *\n   * @returns True if the server is running, false otherwise\n   */\n  public isRunning(): boolean {\n    return this.server !== null && this.server.listening;\n  }\n\n  /**\n   * Gets the underlying Express Application instance.\n   *\n   * @returns The Express Application instance\n   */\n  public getApp(): Application {\n    return this.app;\n  }\n\n  /**\n   * Gets the current server configuration.\n   *\n   * @returns The current mock server configuration\n   */\n  public getConfig(): MockServerConfig {\n    return this.config;\n  }\n\n  /**\n   * Generates a mock server instance from a JSON Schema definition.\n   *\n   * Creates CRUD routes or custom routes based on the schema's x-schemock-routes extension.\n   * Automatically determines resource names and base paths from the schema.\n   *\n   * @param schema - The JSON Schema definition to generate routes from\n   * @param options - Optional server configuration options (defaults to port 3000)\n   * @returns A new ServerGenerator instance configured with routes from the schema\n   */\n  public static generateFromSchema(schema: Schema, options: Partial<ServerOptions> = { port: 3000 }): ServerGenerator {\n    const port = options.port !== undefined ? options.port : 3000;\n\n    const resourceName = determineResourceName(schema, options);\n    const basePath = determineBasePath(resourceName, options);\n\n    const createHandler = (method: string, routePath: string, routeDef: { response?: JSONValue | Schema }, wrap: boolean = true) => {\n      return createRouteHandler(method, routePath, routeDef, schema, options, wrap);\n    };\n\n    const routes = schema['x-schemock-routes'] && Array.isArray(schema['x-schemock-routes'])\n      ? generateCustomRoutes(schema, createHandler)\n      : generateCrudRoutes(basePath, schema, createHandler);\n\n    const config: MockServerConfig = {\n      server: {\n        port,\n        cors: true,\n        logLevel: 'info',\n        ...options\n      },\n      routes\n    };\n\n    return new ServerGenerator(config, true);\n  }\n}\n\n/**\n * Creates a new mock server instance with the specified configuration.\n *\n * This is a convenience function that creates a ServerGenerator instance\n * with the provided configuration.\n *\n * @param config - The mock server configuration containing server settings and route definitions\n * @returns A new ServerGenerator instance\n * @throws {ValidationError} When configuration validation fails\n */\nexport function createMockServer(config: MockServerConfig): ServerGenerator {\n  return new ServerGenerator(config);\n}\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774166182331}}
{"type":"message","id":"0598dce6","parentId":"6d56f051","timestamp":"2026-03-22T07:56:41.178Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the full picture. The `generateFromSchema` creates handlers via `createRouteHandler`, which doesn't know about WorldState. And the `ServerGenerator` stores `this.state: ServerState` which is passed to handlers.\n\nThe cleanest integration path:\n\n1. Add `worldState: WorldState` as a property on `ServerGenerator`\n2. When generating routes in `generateFromSchema`, pass the WorldState into `createRouteHandler`\n3. `createRouteHandler` stores it in a closure and passes it to the handlers\n4. In the handlers, after generating data, use WorldState to resolve FKs before storing\n\n\n5. But I'm realizing there's a constraint here — `createRouteHandler` currently returns a function with the signature `(req: RouteRequest, state: ServerState) => JSONValue`, and I can't easily change that interface without breaking things. The state object itself is just `Record<string, JSONValue[]>`, so I need another way to pass the WorldState through.\n\nThe simplest approach is to attach WorldState directly to the state object under a special key like `state._world = world`. This avoids any interface changes and keeps everything self-contained.\n\nNow I'm tracing through where entities actually get created and stored so I can inject the foreign key resolution logic at the right points in the flow. The core foreign key resolution happens in `SchemaParser.parse()` when generating data, so I need to intercept there to swap in real IDs from the world state instead of generating new ones. I'm tracing through where entities are created and stored across the handler functions. The key entry points are `handlePost` which processes user input, and `handleGetById` and `handleGetCollection` which generate mock data. After entities are created or generated, I need to resolve any foreign key references and then register them with the world state. I should add WorldState to the ServerState object with a special key so it can be passed through without changing the handler signatures. Then I'll add methods to ServerGenerator to set up and manage the world state, and create helper functions in schema-routes to handle the FK resolution and registration on new entities.\n\nActually, modifying ServerGenerator feels invasive. A cleaner approach would be to make WorldState a standalone utility that integrates directly into the state management in schema-routes.ts. I can initialize it lazily on first access, resolve any foreign keys in the generated entity, and register it with the world state. This keeps things decoupled. Now I'll start implementing the WorldState class itself.\n\nImplementing WorldState class... Now I need to think about how to actually wire this into the schema-routes system. The handlers already have access to the `state` object, so I can store the WorldState instance there under a special key. The cleanest approach is to check if WorldState exists in state on first use, create it if needed, then use it to resolve foreign keys on every generated entity before storing anything.\n\nI should also think about the MCP integration angle here - the WorldState snapshot could be exposed as an MCP tool so AI agents can inspect what entities exist in the world. That's a nice way to tie this back into the broader architecture.","thinkingSignature":"4fd31ea64b37df831cd607a4712844d08572910631894db6d211f31083b6a811"},{"type":"text","text":"Good. Now I'll wire WorldState into the schema routes so every entity gets FK-resolved automatically:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_x5gkdrrs4fgy_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\dev\\schemock-app\\src\\generators\\schema-routes.ts","limit":10}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":53929,"output":723,"cacheRead":12454,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":67106,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774166182334}}
