{"type":"message","id":"9e948370","parentId":"49c1abdf","timestamp":"2026-03-22T14:52:21.089Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so two things are actually missing:1. `schemock init \"NL description\"` CLI command2. Semantic field detector in schema-routes.ts (for AI enrichment)\n\nLet me now build these. First, let me understand the `generate_schema` MCP tool - it calls the server's `__schemock/reload` endpoint with a generated schema. But there's no CLI equivalent for `schemock init \"NL description\"`.\n\nLet me build:\n1. `schemock init` CLI command that takes a NL description, uses the schema-inferrer, saves the schema to disk, and boots the server\n2. Semantic field detector in schema-routes.ts\n\n\nActually, the MCP tool already handles the full flow end-to-end: it takes the NL description, calls the schema inferrer to get a generated schema, then hot-reloads the server with it. So I mainly need to expose that same functionality through a CLI command, and potentially add semantic field enrichment to schema-routes.ts for detecting fields like bio, description, title and enhancing them with AI. to generate a schema\n2. Have the MCP tool call a server endpoint that hot-reloads with that schema\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the plan's `schemock init` command:\n```bash\nschemock init \"a blog with users, posts, and comments\"\n# → LLM generates schema\n# → Server boots with all routes live\n# → MCP server running\n```\n\nThis is essentially the same as `generate_schema` MCP tool but run from the CLI. The `schemock init` command would:\n1. Take the NL description as argument\n2. Call the AI provider with schema-inferrer\n3. Write the schema to disk\n4. Start the mock server with that schema\n\nThe MCP tool, on the other hand, would:\n1. Take the NL description\n2. Call the AI provider\n3. Push the schema directly to a running server via `POST /__schemock/reload`\n\nSo the distinction is that CLI initializes and persists, while MCP just hot-reloads an already running instance.\n\nFor the CLI init command, I need to check if there's a dedicated `src/cli/commands/init.ts` or if I should add it directly to the main CLI file. The plan shows it as a new file, but looking at the actual CLI structure, the commands are likely inline. Let me build this as a new command file.\n\nI'm also noticing the MCP server references the AI module with `.js` extensions even though the files are in TypeScript—this might be a build artifact issue, or it could work if the bundler handles the extension translation automatically.\n\nNow I need to focus on what actually matters for getting the product working.","thinkingSignature":"2ed5e8a6159c5f3a3270cf6dad411f5fdeb589e463ba9153ed50f9acaa17df2b"},{"type":"text","text":"\nTwo things actually missing from the plan:\n\n1. **`schemock init \"NL description\"` CLI command** — the killer UX feature\n2. **Semantic field detector** — enriches bio/title/description fields with AI-generated content\n\nLet me build both. Starting with `schemock init`:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vur69w0kjwcn_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\dev\\schemock-app\\src\\cli\\commands\\init.ts","content":"/**\n * schemock init — NL description → running mock server\n * \n * The primary onboarding command.\n * Usage: schemock init \"a blog with users, posts, and comments\"\n */\n\nimport chalk from 'chalk';\nimport { resolve } from 'path';\nimport { writeFileSync, mkdirSync, existsSync } from 'fs';\nimport { createAIProvider } from '../ai/index.js';\nimport { inferSchema } from '../ai/schema-inferrer.js';\nimport { createMockServer } from '../index.js';\nimport type { ServerGenerator } from '../generators/server.js';\n\nexport interface InitOptions {\n  description: string;\n  output?: string;\n  port?: number;\n  open?: boolean;\n  provider?: string;\n  model?: string;\n  aiKey?: string;\n}\n\nexport async function runInit(options: InitOptions): Promise<void> {\n  const {\n    description,\n    output = 'schema.json',\n    port = 3000,\n    provider,\n    model,\n    aiKey,\n  } = options;\n\n  console.log(chalk.blue(`\\n🚀 Schemock: \"${description}\"\\n`));\n  console.log(chalk.gray('Generating your API schema with AI...\\n'));\n\n  // Resolve output path\n  const outputPath = resolve(process.cwd(), output);\n  const outputDir = resolve(process.cwd());\n\n  // Ensure output directory exists\n  if (!existsSync(outputDir)) {\n    mkdirSync(outputDir, { recursive: true });\n  }\n\n  // Create AI provider\n  let aiProvider;\n  try {\n    aiProvider = createAIProvider({\n      provider: provider as any,\n      model,\n      apiKey: aiKey,\n    });\n  } catch (err: any) {\n    console.error(chalk.red(`\\n❌ AI provider error: ${err.message}`));\n    console.error(chalk.yellow('\\nTo use OpenAI:'));\n    console.error(chalk.cyan('   schemock init \"my API\" --ai-key sk-...'));\n    console.error(chalk.gray('   Or set SCHEMOCKER_API_KEY env var\\n'));\n    console.error(chalk.yellow('To use Ollama (local):'));\n    console.error(chalk.cyan('   schemock init \"my API\" --provider ollama'));\n    console.error(chalk.gray('   (Requires Ollama running: ollama serve)\\n'));\n    process.exit(1);\n  }\n\n  // Generate schema via AI\n  let schema: Record<string, unknown>;\n  try {\n    const result = await inferSchema(description, aiProvider, { model });\n    schema = result.schema;\n  } catch (err: any) {\n    console.error(chalk.red(`\\n❌ Schema generation failed: ${err.message}`));\n    process.exit(1);\n  }\n\n  // Write schema to disk\n  writeFileSync(outputPath, JSON.stringify(schema, null, 2));\n  console.log(chalk.green(`✅ Schema generated → ${outputPath}`));\n\n  // Start the mock server\n  console.log(chalk.blue(`\\n🔥 Starting mock server on port ${port}...\\n`));\n\n  let server: InstanceType<typeof ServerGenerator>;\n  try {\n    // Dynamic import to avoid circular issues\n    const { createMockServer } = await import('../index.js');\n    server = createMockServer(schema as any, {\n      port,\n      cors: true,\n      logLevel: 'info',\n    }) as InstanceType<typeof ServerGenerator>;\n    await server.start();\n  } catch (err: any) {\n    if (err.message?.includes('EADDRINUSE')) {\n      console.error(chalk.red(`\\n❌ Port ${port} is already in use.`));\n      console.error(chalk.yellow(`   Try: schemock init \"${description}\" --port ${port + 1}\\n`));\n      process.exit(1);\n    }\n    console.error(chalk.red(`\\n❌ Failed to start server: ${err.message}`));\n    process.exit(1);\n  }\n\n  console.log(chalk.green(`\\n✅ Server running at http://localhost:${port}`));\n  console.log(chalk.blue(`   Playground:  http://localhost:${port}/`));\n  console.log(chalk.blue(`   MCP server: schemocker-mcp\\n`));\n  console.log(chalk.gray('   Press Ctrl+C to stop\\n'));\n\n  // Extract and display the routes\n  const routes = (schema['x-schemock-routes'] as any[]) || [];\n  if (routes.length > 0) {\n    console.log(chalk.bold('\\n📡 Endpoints:'));\n    for (const route of routes) {\n      const method = route.method?.toUpperCase() || 'GET';\n      const path = route.path || '';\n      const desc = route.description ? chalk.gray(` — ${route.description}`) : '';\n      console.log(`   ${chalk.cyan(method.padEnd(8))} ${path}${desc}`);\n    }\n    console.log();\n  }\n\n  console.log(chalk.bold('💡 What you can do next:'));\n  console.log(chalk.cyan('   schemock generate component /api/posts  '), chalk.gray('Generate a React component'));\n  console.log(chalk.cyan('   schemocker-mcp                     '), chalk.gray('Connect to Claude/Cursor\\n'));\n}\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":90843,"output":1795,"cacheRead":12454,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":105092,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774191092003}}
